The smallest readable rewrite is to normalize the three trimmed values once, then express the two output shapes directly.

```ts
type PersonName = {
  first: string;
  last: string;
  nickname?: string;
};

export function makeLabel(p: PersonName, short: boolean): string {
  const first = p.first.trim();
  const last = p.last.trim();
  const nickname = p.nickname?.trim() || "";

  if (short) {
    return nickname || `${first} ${last}`;
  }

  return nickname ? `${last}, ${first} (${nickname})` : `${last}, ${first}`;
}
```

Cleanup boundary: keep it strictly local to value normalization and branch shaping. Trim `first` and `last` exactly when used, collapse missing or whitespace-only `nickname` to `""`, and do not change the exported signature or output formats. No broader refactor is justified here because the helper is already fully specified, pure, and stable.

